{
  "doc_id": "20328",
  "text": "Gibberellins control stem elongation, but can also regulate crown characteristics (Figure 1) . Gibberellin 2-oxidase (GA2ox) overexpression leads to low levels of bioactive GAs, and proliferation of long sylleptic branches at a wide, almost perpendicular angle to the main stem [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . After 2 years in the field, GA2ox overexpressors produced a wide oval crown [CITATION_3] . A similar effect was also observed in turf grass and rice [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These effects are possibly mediated via the GAs regulation of PIN auxin efflux carrier abundance [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . In contrast, modifications of GA signaling via DELLA domain proteins produces a highly compact crown consisting of short branches with narrow acute angle [CITATION_9] . The effect of DELLA domain proteins on branching may be due their interactions with the transcription factor BRANCHED1 [CITATION_10] .",
